{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616902"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16446"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.9,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9137"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74641"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9137"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60135"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1498"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5789"},{"type":"tags","id":"7195"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21709"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74641"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of severe, sharp, electric shock-like pain affecting the right side of her face. The pain occurs in brief episodes lasting seconds to minutes, triggered by washing her face, eating, or exposure to cold wind. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Light touch to the right side of her face triggers a painful episode. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate description of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pain is typically constant and dull","Episodes usually last several hours","Symptoms are triggered by specific activities","Left side of face is more commonly affected","Young adults are most frequently affected"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classical features of trigeminal neuralgia, characterised by paroxysmal, severe, lancinating facial pain in the distribution of one or more branches of the trigeminal nerve. The condition typically affects people over 50 years of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESymptoms are triggered by specific activities\u003C/strong\u003E. Common triggers include washing, eating, talking, brushing teeth, or exposure to cold wind. These trigger zones are areas where light touch can precipitate an attack of pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain is typically constant and dull\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The pain of trigeminal neuralgia is characteristically sharp, electric shock-like, and occurs in brief episodes lasting seconds to minutes, not constant or dull.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpisodes usually last several hours\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Episodes are typically very brief, lasting seconds to minutes. Prolonged episodes are not characteristic of trigeminal neuralgia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft side of face is more commonly affected\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The right side is more commonly affected than the left side, though the reason for this is not fully understood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYoung adults are most frequently affected\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Trigeminal neuralgia typically affects people over 50 years of age, with peak incidence between 60-70 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of classical trigeminal neuralgia is neurovascular compression of the trigeminal nerve root entry zone by an aberrant loop of artery or vein. Secondary causes include multiple sclerosis, tumours, or vascular malformations. First-line treatment involves carbamazepine or oxcarbazepine. Surgical options may be considered in refractory cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trigeminal neuralgia is characterised by paroxysmal, severe, lancinating facial pain in the distribution of one or more branches of the trigeminal nerve.","Common triggers include cold, touch, chewing, talking, or brushing teeth.","Neurovascular compression by aberrant vessels is the most common cause of classical trigeminal neuralgia."],"references":["Maarbjerg S, Di Stefano G, Bendtsen L, Cruccu G. Trigeminal neuralgia - diagnosis and treatment. Cephalalgia. 2017 Jun;37(7):648-657. doi: 10.1177/0333102416687280. Epub 2017 Jan 11. PMID: 28076964.","Gambeta E, Chichorro JG, Zamponi GW. Trigeminal neuralgia: An overview from pathophysiology to pharmacological treatments. Mol Pain. 2020 Jan-Dec;16:1744806920901890. doi: 10.1177/1744806920901890. PMID: 31908187; PMCID: PMC6985973.","Araya EI, Claudino RF, Piovesan EJ, Chichorro JG. Trigeminal Neuralgia: Basic and Clinical Aspects. Curr Neuropharmacol. 2020;18(2):109-119. doi: 10.2174/1570159X17666191010094350. PMID: 31608834; PMCID: PMC7324879.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60135"}},"questi